Question: How do you believe ACME should better support organizations and cultural leaders?

Response ID: resp_4049
Response Text: I would argue that Austin's foundation of existing organizations has been drastically weakened in the past few years. I hope we can all agree that the recent loss of Big Medium is one glaring example in the visual arts sector. The Zilker Theater Production is selling off a huge inventory of high-quality costumed and fully-designed sets because they can't afford the storage expense anymore. We all know who was hit, so I won’t go on. My point is that for those of us who were benefitting from the organizations that lost funding, the result has been disruptive at best, as we’ve lost avenues for showing, selling, performing, and spaces for community connection. At worst it has caused the loss of income and career options. 
And yet, the funds that weren’t awarded to the many established organizations were awarded to artists and communities who deserve this support as well. It’s exciting to see these newly-established organizations popping up. 
My question: Are you talking about all of these groups--from recently closed to freshly launched as that "foundation of existing organization that informs (the)... mission"? Even if it's just the groups and individuals you funded in the past two years, that is A Lot of very different needs to consider. 
This leads me to my answer, which is not an easy one. The city needs to give more than the current funding, which relies heavily on HOT tax revenue. Yes, I know that the city is struggling with budget deficits that include public education and important infrastructure projects. I understand that advocating for more funding is a frustrating answer. But isn’t that what you are asking the arts community to do? To come up with more funding in new and creative ways? How can we work together to do this? And honestly, why aren’t local businesses and wealthy individuals being courted by the city to partner in funding cultural initiatives? 
There are so many more artists (visual, music, writing, performance) in Austin than there were 10 years ago. The needs have evolved along with their markets, the demographics have changed. How much has the city funding changed? As long as you're pitting organizations and individual artists against each other for mostly meager handouts with too meany strings attached, you're never really supporting anyone. Real support would build in greater sustainability.

